<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_4:_6.2_Other_Applications_of_Price_Elasticity">Notes for Week 4: 6.2 Other Applications of Price Elasticity</span></h2>
<p>Inelastic Goods</p>
<p>Drugs      5% Decrease in supply           15% increase in price
<br />
<a href="/wiki/images/3/36/6.2_Other_Applications_of_Price_Elasticity.png" class="image"><img alt="6.2 Other Applications of Price Elasticity.png" src="/wiki/images/3/36/6.2_Other_Applications_of_Price_Elasticity.png" width="554" height="531" /></a>
<ul><li> Note that the Demand for drugs is inelastic (price is extremely sensitive to quantity)
</li><li> When government cracks down on the quantity of drugs sold $$Q&#95;2 - Q&#95;1$$, the resulting price of the drug, $$P&#95;2 - P&#95;1$$, is really big. 
</li><li> Consequently, the revenue the drug dealers receive is even greater than before, giving them even more incentive to deal drugs</p>
</li></ul>

<hr />
<p><br />
Crops      5% Increase in supply           15% decrease in price
<br /><a href="/wiki/images/9/9f/6.2_Other_Applications_of_Price_Elasticity_2.png" class="image"><img alt="6.2 Other Applications of Price Elasticity 2.png" src="/wiki/images/9/9f/6.2_Other_Applications_of_Price_Elasticity_2.png" width="549" height="526" /></a>
<ul><li> Price of crops is also inelastic (because we need them to survive, so we'll have to pay for it regardless of price)
</li><li> When farmers became more productive, the produced more quantity of crops, effectively shifting the Supply curve to the right.
</li><li> But the marginal increase in the quantity supplied caused a major decrease in the price of the crop.</p>
</li></ul>


